{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645975","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645975"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:24:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:24:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18149"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18149"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.04,0.59,0.3,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10863"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78408"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10863"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18149"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63770"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5325"},{"type":"tags","id":"7332"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25272"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25276"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26872"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78408"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe median nerve is a major nerve of the upper limb that provides motor innervation to certain muscles in the hand.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the number of lumbrical muscles supplied by the median nerve?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["0","1","2","3","4"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe median nerve supplies the thenar muscles and the \u003Cstrong\u003Efirst and second lumbrical muscles\u003C/strong\u003E in the hand. These muscles are responsible for flexing the metacarpophalangeal joints and extending the interphalangeal joints of the index and middle fingers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0\u003C/strong\u003E - The median nerve does supply lumbrical muscles\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1\u003C/strong\u003E - The median nerve supplies two lumbricals, not just one\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E3\u003C/strong\u003E - The median nerve does not supply the third lumbrical\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E4\u003C/strong\u003E - The median nerve supplies only the first and second lumbricals, not all four\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe third and fourth lumbrical muscles are supplied by the ulnar nerve.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The median nerve in the hand supplies the thenar muscles and the first and second lumbrical muscles.","The lumbrical muscles are involved in flexing the metacarpophalangeal joints and extending the interphalangeal joints of the fingers.","The ulnar nerve supplies the third and fourth lumbrical muscles."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Raszewski JA, Black AC, Launico MV, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Hand Compartments. [Updated 2023 Oct 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Tr